<P>&startq;Madam <HI>R$gotte, &s;aid I to her,</HI> I beg of you by all
the Charms that render you lovely, to &s;et me at
liberty, and then we'll &s;ee what I can do to
plea&s;e you.&endq; &startq;Oh Traytor! <HI>cry'd &s;he,</HI> if thou lov|ed&s;t
me, thou would&s;t not hone &s;o much after thy
own Kingdom, but would&s;t be content to live in
a Grotto, Wood, or De&s;ert. Don't believe me to
be &s;o great a Novice, thou think&s;t of &s;tealing a|way
but I tell you for your Comfort, you mu&s;t
&s;tay here; and the fir&s;t thing you &s;hall do, &s;hall
<PB N="33" REF="42">
be to keep my Sheep, which have as much Wit,
and &s;peak as well as thou do&s;t.&endq; At the &s;ame time
&s;he brought me into this Plain, where we are
now, and &s;how'd me her Flock, which I looked
on but little, for that beautiful Slave that was
with her took up all my Regard, and my Eyes
betray'd me; which the cruel <HI>R$gotte</HI> ob&s;erving,
flew upon her, and &s;tabb'd her into the Eye with
her Bodkin, and &s;o deprived that adorable Object
